The course is primarily for students of the department of Social Sciences. It is an extensive introductory course to Political Science, which deals with the patterns and processes whereby a society govern itself and includes its members into the processes of political decision-making.  Politics is about power, conflict and inequality in a context, where in core issues there is more than one involved political actor and where parties in the conflict disagree among each other. Therefore, the understanding of political processes depends on the ability to comprehend the political issues according to the divergent experiences, goals and worldviews of the involved parties.Objectives/eesmärkid:  * to give a general and comprehensive overview of Government and Politics * to give an overview of the main ideological approaches that are used in political analysis * to promote citizen competence that is based on moral responsibility and the sense of justice and which formulates his or her positions based on adequate perception of social problems and political controversies.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  * is familiar with the analytical methods of Political Science and is able to use these in the political analysis * understands the essence and substance of politics; * understands the main components that influence political analysis (ideologies, political beliefs); various forms of political participation (interest groups, social movements, parties) * comprehends the complexity of the justice-related political issues, where parties of the conflict have contrasting goals, value orientations and arguments; * is able to formulate and explain a moral position in conflictual political issues (such as related to equality and justice).
